InstanceDepth (ICCV 2025) — Architecture Reconstruction & Implementation Plan
This is a research-first analysis. No code. The goal is to reconstruct the framework faithfully, label every detail by confidence, and give you a roadmap to approve before implementation.

A. Paper Analysis
A.1 What the paper actually builds
InstanceDepth is a two-stage supervised metric-depth framework built on a frozen/finetuned DINOv2 encoder, designed for occlusion-heavy multi-object scenes. The two stages are:

Holistic Depth Initialization (HDI) — produces a coarse scene-level metric depth via iterative depth-range refinement over a multi-scale decoder.
Instance-Aware Depth Rectification (IADR) — a Mask2Former-style decoder predicts instance masks + per-instance depth layers, then an occlusion-pair relation reasoning module corrects depth in overlapping regions.
There is a three-phase training schedule with explicit freeze/unfreeze logic.

A.2 Stage 1 — Holistic Depth Initialization (Sec. 4.1, Fig. 4 & 5)
The depth-range mechanism (the conceptual core). Rather than regress depth directly, the model discretizes depth into rd ranges over MAX_d, then iteratively corrects an initial depth estimate using a learned per-range confidence. The equations:

C_i = Sigmoid(Φd(F_i, D_i)) — depth-range confidence at level i (Eq. 1)
R_i = Σ_{rd} (C_i · S_i) — relative error score, summed over the range dimension (Eq. 2)
E_i = 2·(R_i − 1)·(MAX_d / rd) — relative depth error (Eq. 3)
D_{i+1} = D_i + E_i — refined depth (Eq. 4)
This is repeated across decoder levels (coarse→fine).

The depth-range feature decoder (Fig. 5). Backbone multi-scale features at 1/8, 1/4, 1/2 are each processed by: patch-wise conv (4×4, 8×8, 16×16) → FC layer → patch attention, fused coarse-to-fine to produce "depth range features."

Outputs: Range Seg. Logits S, Range Depth Confidences C, Init Depth Pred D.

A.3 Stage 2 — Instance-Aware Depth Rectification (Sec. 4.2)
Instance Depth Layer Prediction (Sec. 4.2.1, Fig. 7). A Mask2Former-based decoder outputs N predictions, each = {Mask_i, Cls_i, Dep_i} where Dep_i is the instance's average depth (the "depth layer"). A query fusion module produces per-query depth layers. Bipartite matching cost (Eqs. 5–7):

λ1·L_m (mask loss, Mask2Former) + λ2·L_c (classification CE) + λ3·L_d (smoothed L1 on depth layer)
Occlusion-Aware Depth Refinement (Sec. 4.2.2).

Filter instances: category conf > 0.9, mask conf > 0.8.
For each main instance, find overlapping instances (IoU > 0.1), keep the nearest-in-depth as the guest.
Extract multi-scale ROI features F_obj ∈ R^{2×C×Hp×Wp} (the 2 = main+guest pair) and geometric priors G_obj (mask logits, normalized coords, global depths) via ROIAlign.
E_obj = Sigmoid(Φo([F_obj, G_obj])) (Eq. 8)
D̂_obj = [(E_obj×2) − 1]·D̄_obj + D_obj (Eq. 9)
Losses:

L_obj = SigLog(D̂_obj, DT_obj) — scale-invariant log loss (Eq. 10)
L_dist = Σ ||(D̂_i − D̂_j)² − (DT_i − DT_j)²|| — pairwise relative-depth consistency (Eq. 11)
L_ref = λ1·L_obj + λ2·L_dist (Eq. 12)
