what is ROIAlign?....

7 Jun
ROIAlign (Region of Interest Align) is an operation that extracts a fixed-size feature map from an arbitrary rectangular region of a larger feature map — without distorting spatial alignment. It comes from Mask R-CNN (He et al., 2017, reference [23] in your paper).

The problem it solves
Say your backbone produces a feature map at 1/8 resolution, and you have an instance bounding box in image coordinates like [x1=100.3, y1=52.7, x2=210.9, y2=180.1]. You want a neat 7×7×C feature patch for that box to feed into a small head. Two problems:

The box maps to fractional feature-map coordinates after dividing by the stride.
Different boxes have different sizes, but the head needs a fixed shape.
The predecessor, ROIPool, handled this by rounding (quantizing) those fractional coordinates to integer grid cells twice — once mapping the box to the grid, once dividing into bins. Those roundings shift the region by up to a pixel or two, which is fine for coarse detection but wrecks pixel-precise tasks like masks and depth.

What ROIAlign does instead
It keeps the fractional coordinates and uses bilinear interpolation:

Divide the (fractional) ROI into a fixed grid of bins, e.g. 7×7.
In each bin, pick sampling points (typically 4) at sub-pixel locations.
Compute each sample by bilinearly interpolating the 4 nearest feature cells.
Pool (average or max) the samples in each bin.
No rounding anywhere → the output stays geometrically aligned with the input region. Output is always (C, 7, 7) regardless of input box size.

Tensor view
feature map     (B, C, Hf, Wf)          e.g. (1, 256, 65, 65)
boxes           (P, 5)  → [batch_idx, x1, y1, x2, y2]   in feature coords
ROIAlign(output_size=7, sampling_ratio=4)
output          (P, C, 7, 7)             e.g. (P, 256, 7, 7)
P = number of regions; each gets its own fixed (C,7,7) patch.

Where it appears in InstanceDepth
In the Occlusion-Aware Depth Refinement stage (Sec. 4.2.2, Eq. 8). For each occlusion pair (main + guest instance), the paper extracts multi-scale ROI features:

F_obj ∈ R^{2×C×Hp×Wp} via ROIAlign — the 2 is the main+guest pair, Hp×Wp is that fixed output grid.

So ROIAlign is what crops each instance's region out of the shared depth features into a uniform patch, so the MLP Φo can reason about the pair's relative depth.

In practice (your repo)
You won't implement it from scratch — torchvision.ops.roi_align is the standard, battle-tested op:

from torchvision.ops import roi_align
# feats: (B, C, Hf, Wf), boxes: list of (Ni, 4) tensors per image
out = roi_align(feats, boxes, output_size=(7, 7),
                spatial_scale=1/8, sampling_ratio=4, aligned=True)
The one detail that matters: spatial_scale must match the stride of the feature level you're cropping from, and aligned=True applies the half-pixel correction that's now standard. That's the part I flagged as assumption C1 (output size 7×7) in the plan — the paper says ROIAlign but doesn't state the grid size, so we infer the Mask R-CNN default.

