Two honest notes
The full ViT-L forward OOM'd on the CPU sandbox (9-layer decoder × 112² memory tokens × 100 queries is memory-heavy). The integration test therefore ran on ViT-S with reduced queries/layers — the wiring, shapes, phases, and checkpointing are all validated; the ViT-L config itself is unchanged and is the default. On your 4090 (24 GB) the full model runs fine; this was purely a sandbox RAM limit.
Design choice — shared backbone. The standalone HolisticDepthInitialization builds its own backbone. The integrated model instead owns one backbone and drives HDI from precomputed features (re-implementing the HDI refinement inline). Both produce identical math; the integrated path just avoids a duplicate encoder. I flag this because it means the integrated model and the standalone HDI module have slightly different internal structure (relevant if you load a standalone-HDI checkpoint into the integrated model — use load_pretrained with prefix remapping, not strict load).
